WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.702
The President:
Mr. Speaker.

2
00:00:02.702 --> 00:00:07.240
Mr. Vice President.
Members of Congress.

3
00:00:07.240 --> 00:00:09.109
my fellow Americans:

4
00:00:10.577 --> 00:00:14.780
We are 15 years into
this new century.

5
00:00:15.582 --> 00:00:18.385
Fifteen years that dawned
with terror touching

6
00:00:18.385 --> 00:00:22.789
our shores; that unfolded with
a new generation fighting

7
00:00:22.789 --> 00:00:27.127
two long and costly
wars; that saw a vicious

8
00:00:27.127 --> 00:00:30.630
recession spread across
our nation and the world.

9
00:00:33.366 --> 00:00:37.237
It has been. and still
is. a hard time for many.

10
00:00:39.706 --> 00:00:43.943
But tonight. we
turn the page.

11
00:00:43.943 --> 00:00:46.745
Tonight. after a
breakthrough year

12
00:00:46.746 --> 00:00:50.483
for America. our economy
is growing and creating

13
00:00:50.483 --> 00:00:53.986
jobs at the fastest
pace since 1999.

14
00:00:53.987 --> 00:00:59.567
(applause)

15
00:01:17.977 --> 00:01:19.279
Our unemployment
rate is now

16
00:01:19.279 --> 00:01:22.615
lower than it was before
the financial crisis.

17
00:01:22.615 --> 00:01:24.116
More of our kids
are graduating

18
00:01:24.117 --> 00:01:25.885
than ever before.

19
00:01:25.885 --> 00:01:28.621
More of our people are
insured than ever before.

20
00:01:28.621 --> 00:01:32.640
(applause)

21
00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:45.800
And we are as free
from the grip

22
00:01:45.805 --> 00:01:48.708
of foreign oil as we've
been in almost 30 years.

23
00:01:48.708 --> 00:01:52.308
(applause)

24
00:01:57.217 --> 00:02:01.488
Tonight. for the first
time since 9/11.

25
00:02:01.488 --> 00:02:05.525
our combat mission in
Afghanistan is over.

26
00:02:05.525 --> 00:02:10.480
(applause)

27
00:02:10.479 --> 00:02:12.698
Six years ago.
nearly 180.000

28
00:02:12.699 --> 00:02:16.102
American troops served in
Iraq and Afghanistan.

29
00:02:16.102 --> 00:02:19.620
Today. fewer than
15.000 remain.

30
00:02:19.620 --> 00:02:22.876
And we salute the courage
and sacrifice of every man

31
00:02:22.876 --> 00:02:25.612
and woman in this 9/11
Generation who has

32
00:02:25.612 --> 00:02:27.412
served to
keep us safe.

33
00:02:27.413 --> 00:02:28.515
(applause)

34
00:02:28.515 --> 00:02:30.983
We are humbled and
grateful for your service.

35
00:02:30.984 --> 00:02:35.344
(applause)

36
00:03:02.715 --> 00:03:06.185
America. for all that
we have endured;

37
00:03:06.185 --> 00:03:10.290
for all the grit and hard
work required to come back;

38
00:03:10.290 --> 00:03:14.293
for all the tasks that
lie ahead. know this:

39
00:03:14.294 --> 00:03:16.829
The shadow of crisis
has passed. and the

40
00:03:16.829 --> 00:03:19.432
State of the
Union is strong.

41
00:03:19.432 --> 00:03:25.704
(applause)

42
00:03:32.700 --> 00:03:35.915
At this moment -- with
a growing economy.

43
00:03:35.915 --> 00:03:40.786
shrinking deficits. bustling
industry. booming energy

44
00:03:40.787 --> 00:03:44.23
production -- we have
risen from recession

45
00:03:44.23 --> 00:03:47.454
freer to write our own
future than any other

46
00:03:47.460 --> 00:03:50.263
nation on Earth.

47
00:03:50.263 --> 00:03:53.566
It's now up to us to
choose who we want

48
00:03:53.566 --> 00:03:56.536
to be over the next 15 years
and for decades to come.

49
00:03:58.705 --> 00:04:00.773
Will we accept an
economy where only a few

50
00:04:00.773 --> 00:04:03.776
of us do
spectacularly well?

51
00:04:03.776 --> 00:04:05.812
Or will we commit
ourselves to an economy

52
00:04:05.812 --> 00:04:08.147
that generates rising
incomes and chances

53
00:04:08.147 --> 00:04:11.84
for everyone who
makes the effort?

54
00:04:11.84 --> 00:04:17.923
(applause)

55
00:04:18.658 --> 00:04:21.761
Will we approach the world
fearful and reactive.

56
00:04:21.761 --> 00:04:24.197
dragged into costly
conflicts that strain

57
00:04:24.197 --> 00:04:27.333
our military and set
back our standing?

58
00:04:27.333 --> 00:04:30.737
Or will we lead wisely.
using all elements

59
00:04:30.737 --> 00:04:33.239
of our power to defeat
new threats and protect

60
00:04:33.239 --> 00:04:35.659
our planet?

61
00:04:35.660 --> 00:04:38.978
Will we allow ourselves to
be sorted into factions

62
00:04:38.978 --> 00:04:41.558
and turned against
one another?

63
00:04:41.560 --> 00:04:44.517
Or will we recapture the
sense of common purpose

64
00:04:44.517 --> 00:04:46.552
that has always propelled
America forward?

65
00:04:48.955 --> 00:04:52.724
In two weeks. I will send
this Congress a budget

66
00:04:52.725 --> 00:04:57.63
filled with ideas that are
practical. not partisan.

67
00:04:57.63 --> 00:04:59.65
And in the months ahead.
I'll crisscross the

68
00:04:59.65 --> 00:05:03.503
country making a
case for those ideas.

69
00:05:03.503 --> 00:05:06.406
So tonight. I want to
focus less on a checklist

70
00:05:06.406 --> 00:05:10.9
of proposals. and focus
more on the values

71
00:05:10.9 --> 00:05:12.11
at stake in the
choices before us.

72
00:05:14.800 --> 00:05:18.880
It begins with
our economy.

73
00:05:18.885 --> 00:05:22.688
Seven years ago.
Rebekah and Ben Erler

74
00:05:22.689 --> 00:05:26.592
of Minneapolis
were newlyweds.

75
00:05:26.592 --> 00:05:30.996
(laughter)

76
00:05:33.66 --> 00:05:34.900
She waited
tables.

77
00:05:34.901 --> 00:05:37.603
He worked
construction.

78
00:05:37.603 --> 00:05:41.641
Their first child.
Jack. was on the way.

79
00:05:41.641 --> 00:05:45.812
They were young and
in love in America.

80
00:05:45.812 --> 00:05:47.814
And it doesn't get
much better than that.

81
00:05:50.216 --> 00:05:53.186
"If only we had known."
Rebekah wrote to me last

82
00:05:53.186 --> 00:05:56.289
spring. "what was about
to happen to the housing

83
00:05:56.289 --> 00:05:59.558
and construction
market."

84
00:05:59.559 --> 00:06:02.462
As the crisis worsened.
Ben's business dried up.

85
00:06:02.462 --> 00:06:05.364
so he took what jobs he
could find. even if they

86
00:06:05.364 --> 00:06:09.669
kept him on the road for
long stretches of time.

87
00:06:09.669 --> 00:06:12.3
Rebekah took out student
loans and enrolled

88
00:06:12.4 --> 00:06:15.441
in community college. and
retrained for a new career.

89
00:06:17.577 --> 00:06:20.613
They sacrificed
for each other.

90
00:06:20.613 --> 00:06:23.616
And slowly. it
paid off.

91
00:06:23.616 --> 00:06:25.852
They bought
their first home.

92
00:06:25.852 --> 00:06:28.587
They had a second
son. Henry.

93
00:06:28.588 --> 00:06:32.158
Rebekah got a better
job and then a raise.

94
00:06:32.158 --> 00:06:34.393
Ben is back in
construction -- and

95
00:06:34.393 --> 00:06:36.395
home for dinner
every night.

96
00:06:37.897 --> 00:06:41.99
"It is amazing." Rebekah
wrote. "what you can

97
00:06:41.100 --> 00:06:46.172
bounce back from when you
have to...we are a strong.

98
00:06:46.172 --> 00:06:48.274
tight-knit family who
has made it through some

99
00:06:48.274 --> 00:06:52.612
very. very
hard times."

100
00:06:52.612 --> 00:06:55.848
"We are a strong.
tight-knit family who

101
00:06:55.848 --> 00:06:57.917
has made it through some
very. very hard times."

102
00:06:59.752 --> 00:07:03.422
America. Rebekah and
Ben's story is our story.

103
00:07:05.525 --> 00:07:07.560
They represent the
millions who have worked

104
00:07:07.560 --> 00:07:12.398
hard and scrimped. and
sacrificed and retooled.

105
00:07:12.398 --> 00:07:14.934
You are the reason that
I ran for this office.

106
00:07:17.270 --> 00:07:20.6
You are the people I was
thinking of six years

107
00:07:20.6 --> 00:07:23.275
ago today. in the darkest
months of the crisis.

108
00:07:23.276 --> 00:07:26.212
when I stood on the steps of
this Capitol and promised

109
00:07:26.212 --> 00:07:30.650
we would rebuild our economy
on a new foundation.

110
00:07:30.650 --> 00:07:34.320
And it has been your
resilience. your effort

111
00:07:34.320 --> 00:07:36.322
that has made it
possible for our country

112
00:07:36.322 --> 00:07:39.992
to emerge stronger.

113
00:07:39.992 --> 00:07:41.994
We believed we could
reverse the tide

114
00:07:41.994 --> 00:07:45.498
of outsourcing and draw
new jobs to our shores.

115
00:07:45.498 --> 00:07:47.500
And over the past five
years. our businesses

116
00:07:47.500 --> 00:07:49.802
have created more than
11 million new jobs.

117
00:07:49.802 --> 00:08:04.483
(applause)

118
00:08:06.819 --> 00:08:08.588
We believed we could
reduce our dependence

119
00:08:08.588 --> 00:08:11.657
on foreign oil and
protect our planet.

120
00:08:11.657 --> 00:08:15.460
And today. America is
number one in oil and gas.

121
00:08:15.461 --> 00:08:18.731
America is number
one in wind power.

122
00:08:18.731 --> 00:08:21.33
Every three weeks. we
bring online as much

123
00:08:21.33 --> 00:08:25.71
solar power as we
did in all of 2008.

124
00:08:25.71 --> 00:08:26.505
(applause)

125
00:08:26.505 --> 00:08:28.241
And thanks to
lower gas prices

126
00:08:28.241 --> 00:08:30.476
and higher fuel standards.
the typical family

127
00:08:30.476 --> 00:08:34.780
this year should save
about $750 at the pump.

128
00:08:34.780 --> 00:08:39.952
(applause)

129
00:08:42.554 --> 00:08:44.556
We believed we could
prepare our kids for

130
00:08:44.557 --> 00:08:46.325
a more competitive
world.

131
00:08:46.325 --> 00:08:48.427
And today. our younger
students have earned the

132
00:08:48.427 --> 00:08:51.564
highest math and reading
scores on record.

133
00:08:51.564 --> 00:08:53.565
Our high school
graduation rate has

134
00:08:53.566 --> 00:08:55.501
hit an
all-time high.

135
00:08:55.501 --> 00:08:58.971
More Americans finish
college than ever before.

136
00:08:58.971 --> 00:09:05.211
(applause)

137
00:09:05.211 --> 00:09:06.879
We believed that sensible
regulations could

138
00:09:06.879 --> 00:09:10.216
prevent another crisis.
shield families from ruin.

139
00:09:10.216 --> 00:09:13.920
and encourage
fair competition.

140
00:09:13.920 --> 00:09:16.289
Today. we have new tools
to stop taxpayer-funded

141
00:09:16.289 --> 00:09:18.824
bailouts. and a new
consumer watchdog

142
00:09:18.824 --> 00:09:21.593
to protect us from predatory
lending and abusive

143
00:09:21.594 --> 00:09:23.896
credit card
practices.

144
00:09:23.896 --> 00:09:26.598
And in the past year
alone. about 10 million

145
00:09:26.599 --> 00:09:28.701
uninsured Americans
finally gained

146
00:09:28.701 --> 00:09:30.703
the security of
health coverage.

147
00:09:30.703 --> 00:09:32.703
(applause)

148
00:09:48.187 --> 00:09:51.424
At every step. we were
told our goals were

149
00:09:51.424 --> 00:09:55.761
misguided or too
ambitious; that

150
00:09:55.761 --> 00:09:59.865
we would crush jobs
and explode deficits.

151
00:09:59.865 --> 00:10:01.934
Instead. we've seen the
fastest economic growth

152
00:10:01.934 --> 00:10:04.569
in over a decade.
our deficits cut

153
00:10:04.570 --> 00:10:07.740
by two-thirds. a stock
market that has doubled.

154
00:10:07.740 --> 00:10:10.209
and health care inflation
at its lowest rate

155
00:10:10.209 --> 00:10:12.143
in 50 years.

156
00:10:12.144 --> 00:10:17.416
(applause)

157
00:10:25.591 --> 00:10:27.159
This is good
news. people.

158
00:10:27.159 --> 00:10:33.499
(laughter)

159
00:10:33.499 --> 00:10:37.870
(applause)

160
00:10:37.870 --> 00:10:41.73
So the verdict
is clear.

161
00:10:41.73 --> 00:10:44.10
Middle-class
economics works.

162
00:10:44.10 --> 00:10:47.346
Expanding
opportunity works.

163
00:10:47.346 --> 00:10:50.149
And these policies will
continue to work as long

164
00:10:50.149 --> 00:10:53.586
as politics don't
get in the way.

165
00:10:53.586 --> 00:10:55.821
We can't slow down
businesses or put our

166
00:10:55.821 --> 00:10:57.857
economy at risk with
government shutdowns

167
00:10:57.857 --> 00:11:00.925
or fiscal showdowns.

168
00:11:00.926 --> 00:11:03.62
We can't put the security
of families at risk

169
00:11:03.62 --> 00:11:06.699
by taking away their health
insurance. or unraveling

170
00:11:06.699 --> 00:11:09.468
the new rules on Wall
Street. or refighting

171
00:11:09.468 --> 00:11:11.469
past battles on
immigration when we've

172
00:11:11.470 --> 00:11:15.775
got to fix a
broken system.

173
00:11:15.775 --> 00:11:17.776
And if a bill comes
to my desk that tries

174
00:11:17.777 --> 00:11:21.347
to do any of these
things. I will veto it.

175
00:11:21.347 --> 00:11:22.848
It will have
earned my veto.

176
00:11:22.848 --> 00:11:30.55
(applause)

177
00:11:35.494 --> 00:11:37.730
Today. thanks to a growing
economy. the recovery

178
00:11:37.730 --> 00:11:41.233
is touching more
and more lives.

179
00:11:41.233 --> 00:11:44.637
Wages are finally
starting to rise again.

180
00:11:44.637 --> 00:11:46.638
We know that more
small business owners

181
00:11:46.639 --> 00:11:48.641
plan to raise their
employees' pay than

182
00:11:48.641 --> 00:11:52.277
at any time
since 2007.

183
00:11:52.278 --> 00:11:56.415
But here's the thing:
Those of us here tonight.

184
00:11:56.415 --> 00:11:58.918
we need to set our sights
higher than just making

185
00:11:58.918 --> 00:12:01.754
sure government doesn't
screw things up;

186
00:12:01.754 --> 00:12:05.324
that government doesn't halt
the progress we're making.

187
00:12:05.324 --> 00:12:08.861
We need to do more
than just do no harm.

188
00:12:08.861 --> 00:12:13.265
Tonight. together. let's
do more to restore

189
00:12:13.265 --> 00:12:16.635
the link between hard work
and growing opportunity

190
00:12:16.635 --> 00:12:18.404
for every American.

191
00:12:18.404 --> 00:12:23.24
(applause)

192
00:12:34.153 --> 00:12:36.522
Because families
like Rebekah's still

193
00:12:36.522 --> 00:12:38.991
need our help.

194
00:12:38.991 --> 00:12:42.428
She and Ben are working
as hard as ever.

195
00:12:42.428 --> 00:12:45.498
but they've had to forego
vacations and a new car

196
00:12:45.498 --> 00:12:48.734
so that they can pay off student
loans and save for retirement.

197
00:12:51.103 --> 00:12:55.306
Friday night pizza.
that's a big splurge.

198
00:12:55.307 --> 00:12:58.444
Basic childcare for Jack
and Henry costs more than

199
00:12:58.444 --> 00:13:01.479
their mortgage. and almost
as much as a year at the

200
00:13:01.480 --> 00:13:03.482
University of
Minnesota.

201
00:13:05.50 --> 00:13:08.186
Like millions of
hardworking Americans.

202
00:13:08.187 --> 00:13:11.323
Rebekah isn't asking
for a handout. but she

203
00:13:11.323 --> 00:13:14.126
is asking that we look
for more ways to help

204
00:13:14.126 --> 00:13:16.127
families get ahead.

205
00:13:17.263 --> 00:13:19.265
And in fact. at every
moment of economic

206
00:13:19.265 --> 00:13:21.834
change throughout our
history. this country

207
00:13:21.834 --> 00:13:26.473
has taken bold action to
adapt to new circumstances

208
00:13:26.480 --> 00:13:29.575
and to make sure everyone
gets a fair shot.

209
00:13:29.575 --> 00:13:31.277
We set up worker
protections.

210
00:13:31.277 --> 00:13:35.147
Social Security. Medicare.
Medicaid to protect

211
00:13:35.147 --> 00:13:38.751
ourselves from the
harshest adversity.

212
00:13:38.751 --> 00:13:41.687
We gave our citizens
schools and colleges.

213
00:13:41.687 --> 00:13:44.690
infrastructure and the
Internet -- tools they

214
00:13:44.690 --> 00:13:47.26
needed to go as far as
their effort and their

215
00:13:47.26 --> 00:13:50.94
dreams will
take them.

216
00:13:50.95 --> 00:13:52.998
That's what middle-class
economics is --

217
00:13:52.998 --> 00:13:56.368
the idea that this country
does best when everyone gets

218
00:13:56.368 --> 00:14:00.940
their fair shot. everyone
does their fair share.

219
00:14:00.940 --> 00:14:03.142
everyone plays by the
same set of rules.

220
00:14:03.142 --> 00:14:09.81
(applause)

221
00:14:11.140 --> 00:14:12.718
We don't just want
everyone to share

222
00:14:12.718 --> 00:14:14.719
in America's success.
we want everyone

223
00:14:14.720 --> 00:14:16.589
to contribute to
our success.

224
00:14:16.589 --> 00:14:22.61
(applause)

225
00:14:22.61 --> 00:14:24.196
So what does middle-class
economics require

226
00:14:24.196 --> 00:14:26.198
in our time?

227
00:14:27.533 --> 00:14:30.736
First. middle-class
economics means helping

228
00:14:30.736 --> 00:14:33.973
working families feel
more secure in a world

229
00:14:33.973 --> 00:14:36.973
of constant change.

230
00:14:36.980 --> 00:14:39.840
That means helping folks
afford childcare. college.

231
00:14:39.845 --> 00:14:43.115
health care. a
home. retirement.

232
00:14:43.115 --> 00:14:46.619
And my budget will address
each of these issues.

233
00:14:46.619 --> 00:14:48.754
lowering the taxes
of working families

234
00:14:48.754 --> 00:14:50.956
and putting thousands
of dollars back into

235
00:14:50.956 --> 00:14:52.57
their pockets
each year.

236
00:14:52.57 --> 00:14:57.563
(applause)

237
00:14:59.865 --> 00:15:01.367
Here's one
example.

238
00:15:01.367 --> 00:15:03.235
During World War
II. when men like

239
00:15:03.235 --> 00:15:07.439
my grandfather went off to war.
having women like my grandmother

240
00:15:07.439 --> 00:15:11.810
in the workforce was a
national security priority

241
00:15:11.810 --> 00:15:14.113
-- so this country provided
universal childcare.

242
00:15:16.215 --> 00:15:18.684
In today's economy. when
having both parents in the

243
00:15:18.684 --> 00:15:21.553
workforce is an economic necessity

244
00:15:21.553 --> 00:15:24.757
for many families. we need
affordable. high-quality

245
00:15:24.757 --> 00:15:26.891
childcare more
than ever.

246
00:15:26.892 --> 00:15:31.352
(applause)

247
00:15:43.42 --> 00:15:47.780
It's not a nice-to-have
-- it's a must-have.

248
00:15:47.780 --> 00:15:50.281
So it's time we stop
treating childcare

249
00:15:50.282 --> 00:15:54.820
as a side issue. or as a
women's issue. and treat

250
00:15:54.820 --> 00:15:58.90
it like the national
economic priority that

251
00:15:58.90 --> 00:16:01.93
it is for all of us.

252
00:16:01.93 --> 00:16:08.12
